    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-09-30T07:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-09-30T07:10:00-05:00" n="77"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <head>77. Telegram 5465 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Jordan</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d77fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970-73, AV 12. Secret;
                        Flash. Repeated to Tel Aviv, Bern, Bonn, London, and Geneva.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d77fn2">At the request of the <gloss
                            target="#t_PFLP1">PFLP</gloss>, the United Arab Republic provided a list
                        of names of the detained fedayeen to be released in exchange for the
                        remaining hostages.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Amman</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1970-09-30T12:10:00+00:00">September 30, 1970,
                    1210Z</date>.</dateline>
                <p>Subj: Hijack List</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>At 1215 local September 30, <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> Second
                        Secretary turned over list of names of detainees to be released as quid pro
                        quo for release hostages. Names being sent <gloss target="#t_Septel1"
                            >septel</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Interlocutor made following points as arguments for compliance with
                        fedayeen demands this subject: <list>
                            <label>A.</label>
                            <item>He (the interlocutor) who spoke in name of Fedayeen Central
                                Committee said that if demands are met fedayeen movement will give
                                word of honor that there will be no future hijackings.</item>
                            <label>B.</label>
                            <item>Number of detainees to be released is 56—same as number of
                                hostages released. German, Swiss and British Governments have
                                already announced willingness to release “seven.” <gloss
                                    target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> has agreed to release
                                Algerians.</item>
                            <label>C.</label>
                            <item>Ten Lebanese plus two Algerians are not members of <pb
                                    facs="d77-02" n="2" xml:id="d77-02"/> fedayeen organizatlons.
                                Total number of fedayeen to be released is 44.</item>
                            <label>D.</label>
                            <item>Interlocutor stressed that if demands are met, this would be
                                strong weapon to use in convincing fedayeen that goal can best be
                                reached through negotiation. frustration of this effort might have
                                opposite effect—i.e., that escalating violence is only way to
                                achieve results.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Embassy comment: We are skeptical about value of pledge re no future
                        hijackings. At same time, public statement eschewing such activity would be
                        of such obvious value that efforts to obtain it worth considerable risk.
                        Although interlocutor hardly in position to speak for fedayeen movement, we
                        must give him credit for qte bringing home the bacon unqte on final hostage
                        release.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BEA1">Brown</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
